#!/usr/pkg/bin/bash

# Choose a random line

F=$HOME/html/rss/dhammapada.txt

TOTLINES=`wc -l $F|awk '{print $1}'`

LINENUM=$[($RANDOM%${TOTLINES})+1]

RND=`sed -n "$LINENUM"p $F | awk -F '|' '{print $1}'`

###echo $RND

perl -pi -e "s/<item>.*/<item><title>$RND<\/title><\/item>/" $HOME/html/rss/dhammapada.rss


#All states of being are determined by mind.<BR> It is mind that leads the way.<BR> Just as the wheel of the oxcart follows <BR> the hoof print of the animal that draws it, <BR> so suffering will surely follow <BR> when we speak or act impulsively<BR> from an impure state of mind.|I. THE PAIRS 1
#All states of being are determined by mind.<BR> It is mind that leads the way.<BR> As surely as our shadow never leaves us,<BR> so well-being will follow <BR> when we speak or act <BR> with a pure state of mind.|I. THE PAIRS 2
#When we hold fast to such thoughts as,<BR> "They abused me, mistreated me, <BR> molested me, robbed me,"<BR> we keep hatred alive.|I. THE PAIRS 3
#If we thoroughly release ourselves <BR> from such thoughts as,<BR> "They abused me, mistreated me, <BR> molested me, robbed me,"<BR> hatred is vanquished.|I. THE PAIRS 4
#Never by hatred is hatred conquered, <BR> but by readiness to love alone.<BR> This is eternal law.|I. THE PAIRS 5
#Those who are contentious <BR> have forgotten that we all die;<BR> for the wise, who reflect on this fact, <BR> there are no quarrels.|I. THE PAIRS 6
#As a stormy wind can uproot a frail tree <BR> so one who holds heedlessly to pleasure, <BR> who indulges in food and is indolent, <BR> can be uprooted by Mara |I. THE PAIRS 7
#As a stormy wind <BR> cannot move a mountain of rock <BR> so one who contemplates <BR> the reality of the body, <BR> who develops faith and energy,<BR> is unmoved by Mara.|I. THE PAIRS 8
#Wearing the robe of a renunciate <BR> does not in itself render one pure. <BR> Those who wear it, and yet lack diligence, <BR> are heedless.|I. THE PAIRS 9
#Being possessed of self-restraint,<BR> honest and diligent in conduct;<BR> such a one is worthy <BR> of the renunciate's robe.|I. THE PAIRS 10
#Mistaking the false for the real <BR> and the real for the false,<BR> one suffers a life of falsity.	|I. THE PAIRS 11
#But, seeing the false as the false <BR> and the real as the real,<BR> one lives in the perfectly real.|I. THE PAIRS 12
#Like rain leaking through <BR> a poorly-thatched roof, <BR> the unruly passions <BR> seep into an untamed heart.|I. THE PAIRS 13
#As rain cannot penetrate <BR> a well-thatched roof, <BR> so the passions <BR> cannot enter a well-trained heart. |I. THE PAIRS 14
#When we see clearly <BR> our own lack of virtue <BR> we are filled with grief;<BR> here and hereafter we grieve.|I. THE PAIRS 15
#When we appreciate fully <BR> the benefit of our own pure deeds <BR> we are filled with joy;	<BR> here and hereafter <BR> there is a celebration of joy.|I. THE PAIRS 16
#Here and hereafter <BR> those who perform evil <BR> create their own suffering.<BR> Mental preoccupation 	<BR> with the thought, "I have done wrong" <BR> possesses their minds, <BR> and they fall into chaos.|I. THE PAIRS 17
#Here and hereafter <BR> those who live their lives well <BR> abide in happiness.<BR> They are filled <BR> with a natural appreciation of virtue,<BR> and they dwell in delight.|I. THE PAIRS 18
#Though one may know <BR> much about Dhamma,<BR> if one does not live accordingly  - <BR> like a cowherd <BR> who covets another's cattle  - <BR> one experiences none of the benefits <BR> of walking the Way.|I. THE PAIRS 19
#Knowing only a little about Dhamma<BR> but wholeheartedly according with it,<BR> transforming the passions <BR> of greed, hatred and delusion,<BR> releasing all attachments to here and hereafter,<BR> one will indeed experience for oneself <BR> the benefits of walking the Way.|I. THE PAIRS 20
#Appreciative awareness leads to life;<BR> heedless avoidance is the path to death. <BR> Those who are aware are fully alive,<BR> while those who are heedless <BR> are as if already dead.|II. AWARENESS 21
#The wise, being fully alive, rejoice<BR> in appreciative awareness,<BR> and abide delighting <BR> in this capacity.|II. AWARENESS 22
#The Awakened Ones, firm in their resolve, <BR> vigorously apply themselves,<BR> and know freedom from bondage:<BR> liberation, true security.|II. AWARENESS 23
#Those who are energetically <BR> committed to the Way, <BR> who are pure and considerate in effort,<BR> composed and virtuous in conduct,<BR> steadily increase in radiance.|II. AWARENESS 24
#By endeavour, vigilance, <BR> restraint and self-control, <BR> let the wise make islands of themselves <BR> which no flood can overwhelm.|II. AWARENESS 25
#Those who are foolish and confused<BR> betray themselves to heedlessness.<BR> The wise treasure the awareness<BR> they have cultivated <BR> as their most precious possession.|II. AWARENESS 26
#"Do not become lost in negligence, do not become lost in sensuality."<BR> Heeding such council,<BR> the contemplative discovers <BR> profound release.|II. AWARENESS 27
#Those Awakened Ones, <BR> who have tasted freedom <BR> from all distraction <BR> by cultivating awareness,<BR> view all who are suffering<BR> with compassionate perspective, <BR> as one on a mountaintop<BR> is able to view the plains.|II. AWARENESS 28
#Aware among those who are heedless,<BR> awake among those who sleep,<BR> the wise go forward like strong young horses, <BR> leaving the exhausted behind.|II. AWARENESS 29
#By way of diligent awareness<BR> the god Magha won his realm.<BR> Diligence is ever rewarded,<BR> negligence is ever scorned.|II. AWARENESS 30
#The renunciate who delights in vigilance <BR> and shuns heedlessness<BR> advances like a grass fire,<BR> consuming obstructions great and small.|II. AWARENESS 31
#The renunciate who delights in vigilance <BR> and shuns heedlessness<BR> is protected from regression:<BR> such a one approaches liberation.|II. AWARENESS 32
#Just as a fletcher shapes an arrow,<BR> so the wise develop the mind;<BR> so excitable, uncertain <BR> and difficult to control.|III. THE MIND 33
#Like a fish which on being dragged <BR> from its home in the water <BR> and tossed on dry land <BR> will thrash about,<BR> so will the heart tremble<BR> when withdrawing from the current of Mara.|III. THE MIND 34
#The active mind is difficult to tame, <BR> flighty and wandering wherever it wills:<BR> taming it is essential,<BR> leading to the joy of well-being.|III. THE MIND 35
#The protected and guarded mind<BR> leads to ease of being.<BR> Though subtle, elusive and hard to see,<BR> one who is alert <BR> should tend and watch over this mind.|III. THE MIND 36
#Wandering far and wide on its own,<BR> without form, <BR> the mind lies in the heart-cavern within.<BR> To bring it under control<BR> is to be freed from the bonds of ignorance.|III. THE MIND 37
#In one whose mind is unsteady,<BR> whose heart is not prepared <BR> with true teachings, <BR> whose faith is not matured,<BR> the fullness of wisdom is not yet manifest.|III. THE MIND 38
#There is no fear<BR> if the heart is uncontaminated <BR> by the passions<BR> and the mind is free from ill-will.<BR> Seeing beyond good and evil <BR> one is awake.|III. THE MIND 39
#Seeing this body to be as fragile as a clay vessel,<BR> and fortifying the heart like a city wall,<BR> one can confront Mara with the weapon of insight.<BR> Having the advantage of non-attachment,<BR> one protects what has already been gained.|III. THE MIND 40
#Certainly this body will soon lie lifeless: <BR> cast aside on the ground,<BR> devoid of consciousness<BR> and as useless as a burnt-out log.|III. THE MIND 41
#More than a thief,<BR> more than an enemy,<BR> a misdirected heart <BR> brings one to harm.|III. THE MIND 42
#Neither mother, father<BR> nor any member of a family<BR> can give you the blessings generated<BR> by your own well-directed heart.|III. THE MIND 43
#Who is it <BR> that can truly see as they are<BR> this earth, this body, <BR> the hell realms and the heavenly realms?<BR> Who can discern <BR> the well-taught Path of Wisdom,<BR> in the way the eye of a skilled florist<BR> can select perfect blooms?|IV. FLOWERS 44
#It is those who knowingly walk the Way<BR> who can see as they truly are <BR> this earth, this body, <BR> the hell realms and the heavenly realms.<BR> These are the ones who can discern <BR> the well-taught Path of Wisdom.|IV. FLOWERS 45
#Know the body <BR> to be as transient as foam, a mirage.<BR> The flower of sensual passion<BR> has a hidden barb.<BR> See this and pass beyond death.|IV. FLOWERS 46
#As a flash flood <BR> can sweep away a sleeping village, <BR> so death can destroy<BR> those who only seek the flowers<BR> of casual sensual pleasures.|IV. FLOWERS 47
#To be frustrated and ungratified,<BR> yet still only seek the flowers <BR> of casual sensual pleasures <BR> brings one under the destroyer's sway.|IV. FLOWERS 48
#As a bee gathering nectar <BR> does not harm or disturb <BR> the colour and fragrance of the flower,<BR> so do the wise move<BR> through the world.|IV. FLOWERS 49
#Dwell not on the faults <BR> and shortcomings of others, <BR> instead, seek clarity<BR> about your own.|IV. FLOWERS 50
#As a beautiful flower <BR> without fragrance is disappointing,<BR> so are wise words <BR> without right action.|IV. FLOWERS 51
#As a beautiful flower <BR> with a delightful fragrance is pleasing, <BR> so is wise and lovely speech <BR> when matched with right action.|IV. FLOWERS 52
#As many garlands can be made <BR> from a heap of flowers, <BR> so too, much that is wholesome can be done <BR> during this human existence.|IV. FLOWERS 53
#The fragrance of flowers or sandalwood<BR> blows only with the prevailing wind,<BR> but the fragrance of virtue<BR> pervades all directions.|IV. FLOWERS 54
#The fragrance of virtue <BR> surpasses by far <BR> the fragrance of flowers <BR> or sandalwood.|IV. FLOWERS 55
#The aroma of sandalwood <BR> and the scent of flowers <BR> bring only little delight<BR> compared to the fragrance of virtue,<BR> which suffuses even the heavenly realms.|IV. FLOWERS 56
#It is not possible for Mara to find <BR> those who abide in appreciative awareness <BR> who, by perfect knowledge, are freed <BR> and live in virtue.|IV. FLOWERS 57
#Just as a sweet-smelling and beautiful lotus <BR> can grow from a pile of discarded waste, <BR> the radiance of a true disciple of the Buddha<BR> outshines dark shadows cast by ignorance.|V. FLOWERS 58-59
#The night is long <BR> for one who cannot sleep. <BR> A journey is long for one who is tired. <BR> Ignorant existence is long and tedious<BR> for those unaware of Truth.|V. THE FOOLISH 60
#Having found no companion<BR> who has travelled at least as far as ourselves, <BR> it is better to go alone <BR> than to accompany those <BR> who remain irresolute.|V. THE FOOLISH 61
#"This is my child, this is my wealth": such thoughts are the preoccupations of fools.<BR> If we are unable to own even ourselves, <BR> why make such claims?|V. THE FOOLISH 62
#The fool who knows he is a fool <BR> is at least a little wise; <BR> the fool who thinks that he is wise <BR> is assuredly a fool.|V. THE FOOLISH 63
#Like spoons unable to taste<BR> the flavour of the soup, <BR> are the fools who cannot see truth,<BR> even though they live <BR> all their lives among the wise.|V. THE FOOLISH 64
#Like the tongue that can appreciate<BR> the flavour of the soup, <BR> is one who can discern clearly the truth<BR> after only a brief<BR> association with the wise.|V. THE FOOLISH 65
#By heedlessly performing evil,<BR> the unwary fools <BR> produce their own bitter fruits.<BR> They behave like their worst enemy. |V. THE FOOLISH 66
#A deed is not well-done <BR> when upon reflection remorse arises:<BR> with tears of sorrow <BR> one harvests its fruit.|V. THE FOOLISH 67
#A deed is well-done <BR> when upon reflection no remorse arises: <BR> with joy one harvests its fruits.|V. THE FOOLISH 68
#Fools perceive evil acts <BR> to be sweet as honey <BR> until they have seen the consequences.<BR> When they behold their fruits, <BR> fools suffer indeed.|V. THE FOOLISH 69
#Even after months of rigid asceticism,<BR> subsisting on a frugal diet, <BR> a fool is not to be compared in value<BR> to the person who simply sees the truth.|V. THE FOOLISH 70
#Fresh milk does not immediately <BR> turn into curd,<BR> and evil acts do not immediately <BR> show their fruits;<BR> however, fools do suffer from the consequences<BR> of their foolishness<BR> as they would be burned <BR> by standing on coals hidden in ashes.|V. THE FOOLISH 71
#Fools are those who use foolishly <BR> whatever gifts they have, <BR> destroying their accumulated good fortune.|V. THE FOOLISH 72
#The conceit and craving of fools grows <BR> as they claim for themselves <BR> undue authority, recognition and reward: <BR> their falsity affects their longing,<BR> they wish to be seen <BR> as powerful and discerning.|V. THE FOOLISH 73-74
#Like the tongue that can appreciate<BR> the flavour of the soup, <BR> is one who can discern clearly the truth<BR> after only a brief<BR> association with the wise.|V. THE FOOLISH 75
#Only blessings can arise <BR> from seeking the company <BR> of wise and discerning persons,<BR> who skilfully offer <BR> both admonition and advice<BR> as if guiding one to hidden treasure.|VI. THE WISE 76
#Let the wise guide beings away from darkness, <BR> give direction and advice.<BR> They will be treasured by the virtuous<BR> and dismissed by the foolish.|VI. THE WISE 77
#Do not seek the company of misguided friends;<BR> beware of degenerate companions.<BR> Seek and enjoy the company of well-guided friends, <BR> those who support insight. |VI. THE WISE 78
#Surrendering oneself to Dhamma <BR> leads to serene being. <BR> The wise perpetually delight in the truth <BR> taught by the Awakened One.|VI. THE WISE 79
#Those who build canals <BR> channel the flow of water. <BR> Arrowsmiths make arrows. <BR> Woodworkers craft wood.<BR> The wise tame themselves.|VI. THE WISE 80
#As solid rock<BR> is unshaken by the wind, <BR> so are those with wisdom undisturbed <BR> whether by praise or blame. |VI. THE WISE 81
#On hearing true teachings,<BR> the hearts of those who are receptive,<BR> become serene, <BR> like a lake, deep, clear and still. |VI. THE WISE 82
#Virtuous beings are unattached. <BR> They do not indulge in heedless speech <BR> about sensual pleasures.<BR> They experience both joy and sorrow <BR> but are possessed by neither.|VI. THE WISE 83
#Neither for one's own sake <BR> nor on behalf of another<BR> does a wise person do harm <BR> - not for the sake of family, fortune or gain.<BR> Such a one is rightly called <BR> just, virtuous and wise.|VI. THE WISE 84
#Few are those who reach the beyond. <BR> Most pace endlessly back and forth,<BR> not daring to risk the journey.|VI. THE WISE 85
#Although it is difficult  to cross over <BR> the storm-swept sea of passion, <BR> those who live in accord <BR> with the well-taught Way <BR> arrive at the beyond.|VI. THE WISE 86
#With an image of liberation as the goal <BR> the wise abandon darkness <BR> and cherish light,<BR> leave petty security behind<BR> and seek freedom from attachment.<BR> To pursue such release is difficult and rare, <BR> yet the wise will seek it, <BR> detaching themselves from obstructions, <BR> purifying heart and mind.|VI. THE WISE 87-88
#Freeing themselves from longing,<BR> unhindered by habitual grasping, <BR> those who align themselves with the Way <BR> delight in non-attachment<BR> and, while still in the world,<BR> are radiant.|VI. THE WISE 89
#There is no tension<BR> for those who have completed their journey <BR> and have become free 	<BR> from the distress of bondage.|VII. THE AWAKENED ONE 90
#Alert to the needs of the journey,<BR> those on the path of awareness,<BR> like swans, glide on,<BR> leaving behind their former resting places.|VII. THE AWAKENED ONE 91
#Just like birds that leave no tracks in the air,<BR> there are those whose minds do not cling<BR> to temptations that are offered to them. <BR> Their focus is the signless state of liberation,<BR> which to others is indiscernible. |VII. THE AWAKENED ONE 92
#There are those who are free from all obstructions;<BR> they do not worry about food,<BR> their focus is the signless state of liberation.<BR> Like birds flying through the air,<BR> trackless they move on their way.|VII. THE AWAKENED ONE 93
#Like horses well-trained by their owners <BR> are those who have rightly tamed their senses; <BR> having freed their hearts from pride and pollution <BR> they generate all-pervading delight.|VII. THE AWAKENED ONE 94
#There are those who discover <BR> they can leave behind confused reactions <BR> and become patient as the earth;<BR> unmoved by anger,<BR> unshaken as a pillar,<BR> unperturbed as a clear and quiet pool.|VII. THE AWAKENED ONE 95
#Those who arrive <BR> at the state of perfect freedom <BR> through right understanding<BR> are unperturbed <BR> in body, speech or mind. <BR> They remain unshaken <BR> by life's vicissitudes.|VII. THE AWAKENED ONE 96
#Those who know the uncreated, <BR> who are free and stilled,<BR> who have discarded all craving, <BR> are the most worthy beings.|VII. THE AWAKENED ONE 97
#Whether in a forest, <BR> a town or open country, <BR> delightful is the dwelling place <BR> of one now fully free.|VII. THE AWAKENED ONE 98
#Beings free from addiction to sensual pleasures<BR> know a unique form of delight.<BR> They seek quiet in forest retreats<BR> which worldly beings would avoid.|VII. THE AWAKENED ONE 99
#A single word of truth, <BR> which calms the mind,<BR> is better to hear than a thousand<BR> irrelevant words.|VIII. THE THOUSANDS 100
#A single verse of truth,<BR> which calms the mind,<BR> is better to hear than a thousand<BR> irrelevant verses.|VIII. THE THOUSANDS 101
#Reciting a single verse of truth <BR> which calms the mind<BR> is better than reciting<BR> a hundred meaningless verses.|VIII. THE THOUSANDS 102
#One might defeat alone in battle <BR> a thousand thousand men,<BR> but one who gains self-mastery <BR> is by far the greater hero.|VIII. THE THOUSANDS 103
#Self-mastery is the supreme victory -<BR> much more to be valued <BR> than winning control over others. <BR> It is a victory <BR> that no other being whatsoever<BR> can distort or take away.|VIII. THE THOUSANDS 104-105
#To honour,<BR> even for a single moment,<BR> one who has attained self-mastery, <BR> is of greater merit <BR> than making countless offerings <BR> to those who are unworthy.|VIII. THE THOUSANDS 106
#To honour,<BR> even for a single moment,<BR> one who has attained self-mastery, <BR> is of greater benefit <BR> than habitually performing ceremonies <BR> based on a wrong understanding.|VIII. THE THOUSANDS 107
#Even if one should spend<BR> an entire year<BR> making gestures of offering <BR> for the sake of self-gain, <BR> all this is not worth one quarter the value<BR> of offering veneration to a noble being.|VIII. THE THOUSANDS 108
#For one who always honours and respects<BR> those of greater years,<BR> there are four blessings:<BR> long life, beauty, happiness and strength.|VIII. THE THOUSANDS 109
#A single day lived <BR> with conscious intention and virtue <BR> is of greater value than a hundred years<BR> lived devoid of discipline and right restraint.|VIII. THE THOUSANDS 110
#A single day lived <BR> with conscious intention and wisdom<BR> is of greater value than a hundred years<BR> lived devoid of discipline and manifest wisdom.|VIII. THE THOUSANDS 111
#A single day lived <BR> with conscious intention and profound effort <BR> is of greater value than a hundred years<BR> lived in lazy passivity.|VIII. THE THOUSANDS 112
#A single day lived in awareness <BR> of the transient nature of life <BR> is of greater value than a hundred years<BR> lived unaware of birth and death.|VIII. THE THOUSANDS 113
#A single day lived awake to the undying state <BR> is of greater value than a hundred years<BR> lived without recognising deathlessness.|VIII. THE THOUSANDS 113
#A single day lived awake to profound truth <BR> is of greater value than a hundred years <BR> lived unawakened.|VIII. THE THOUSANDS 115
#Hasten towards doing what is wholesome.<BR> Restrain your mind from evil acts.<BR> The mind that is slow to do good<BR> can easily find pleasure in evil-doing.|IX. EVIL 116
#If you perform an evil act,<BR> then do not repeat it.<BR> Avoid finding pleasure in its memory. <BR> The aftermath of evil-doing is painful.|IX. EVIL 117
#Having performed a wholesome act<BR> it is good to repeat it.<BR> Enjoy the pleasure of its memory. <BR> The fruit of goodness is contentment.|IX. EVIL 118
#Even those who perform evil <BR> can experience well-being <BR> so long as their actions <BR> have not yet borne direct fruits. <BR> However, when the results <BR> of their actions ripen,<BR> the painful consequences<BR> cannot be avoided.|IX. EVIL 119
#Even those who live wholesome lives <BR> can experience suffering <BR> so long as their acts <BR> have not yet borne direct fruits. <BR> However, when the fruits <BR> of their actions ripen<BR> the joyful consequences <BR> cannot be avoided.|IX. EVIL 120
#Do not ignore the effects of evil, <BR> saying, "This will come to nothing."<BR> Just as by the gradual fall of raindrops <BR> the water jar is filled,<BR> so in time fools are corrupted<BR> by evil-doing.|IX. EVIL 121
#Do not ignore the effect of right action<BR> saying, "This will come to nothing."<BR> Just as by the gradual fall of raindrops <BR> the water jar is filled,<BR> so in time the wise <BR> become replete with good.|IX. EVIL 122
#As one who is entrusted with precious cargo<BR> would remain vigilant and protective<BR> avoid evil as if it were poison.|IX. EVIL 123
#A hand without an open wound <BR> can carry poison <BR> and remain free from harm; <BR> likewise, evil has no consequences <BR> for those who do not perform it.|IX. EVIL 124
#If you intentionally harm <BR> an innocent person, <BR> someone who is pure and blameless,<BR> the harm will come back to you <BR> like fine dust thrown into the wind.|IX. EVIL 125
#Some are reborn as humans; <BR> evil-doers are reborn in hell.<BR> Doers of good are reborn in bliss <BR> and the pure enter the trackless land.|IX. EVIL 126
#There is no place on earth<BR> where one can hide <BR> from the consequences of evil actions -<BR> not in a mountain cave,<BR> the ocean nor in the sky.|IX. EVIL 127
#There is no place on earth<BR> beyond the reach of death  -<BR> not in a mountain cave, <BR> the ocean nor in the sky.|IX. EVIL 128
#Having empathy for others <BR> one sees that all beings are afraid<BR> of punishment and death.<BR> Knowing this, <BR> one does not attack or cause attack.|X. AGGRESSION 129
#Having empathy for others <BR> one sees that all beings <BR> love life and fear death. <BR> Knowing this, <BR> one does not attack or cause attack.|X. AGGRESSION 130
#To harm live beings<BR> who, like us, seek contentment, <BR> is to bring harm to ourselves.|X. AGGRESSION 131
#To avoid bringing harm to living beings<BR> who, like us, seek contentment, <BR> is to bring happiness to ourselves.|X. AGGRESSION 132
#Avoid speaking harshly to others;<BR> harsh speech prompts retaliation.<BR> Those hurt by your words may hurt you back.|X. AGGRESSION 133
#If spoken to harshly,<BR> make yourself as silent as a cracked gong;<BR> non-retaliation is a sign of freedom.|X. AGGRESSION 134
#Just as a herdsman <BR> drives cattle to pasture, <BR> old age and death <BR> direct living beings.|X. AGGRESSION 135
#Though while they perform their evil acts <BR> they do not realise what they are doing,<BR> fools suffer the results <BR> of their own actions accordingly, <BR> just as one is burnt when handling fire.|X. AGGRESSION 136
#To cause harm to the defenceless <BR> soon brings suffering <BR> to those who attack.<BR> They will reap pain or poverty or loss,<BR> illness, insanity or persecution,<BR> abuse, distress or devastation,<BR> and, alone, after death <BR> they must confront their misdeeds.|X. AGGRESSION 137-140
#Not outer asceticisms,<BR> nor self-humiliation<BR> nor physical deprivation of any kind,<BR> can purify the heart <BR> of one still obscured by doubt.|X. AGGRESSION 141
#Flamboyant outer appearance<BR> does not in itself constitute <BR> an obstruction to freedom.<BR> Having a heart at peace,<BR> pure, contained, <BR> awake and blameless,<BR> distinguishes a renunciate, <BR> a Wayfarer, a noble being.|X. AGGRESSION 142
#A well-trained horse <BR> gives no cause for restraint.<BR> Rare are those beings who,<BR> through modesty and discipline, <BR> give no cause for rebuke.|X. AGGRESSION 143
#Let the dread of endless mediocrity<BR> spur you into great effort,<BR> like a well-trained horse<BR> encouraged by the mere touch of the whip.<BR> Relinquish the burden of endless struggle<BR> with unapologetic confidence,<BR> with purity of action, effort, concentration,<BR> and by conscious and disciplined commitment<BR> to the path.|X. AGGRESSION 144
#Those who build canals <BR> channel the flow of water. <BR> Arrowsmiths make arrows. <BR> Woodworkers craft wood.<BR> The good tame themselves.|X. AGGRESSION 145
#Why is there laughter?<BR> Why is there joy <BR> when the world is on fire? <BR> Since you are clouded in darkness<BR> should you not seek the light?|XI. OLD AGE 146
#Gaze upon this once-decorated body  -<BR> it used to attract attention<BR> but now it is only festering flesh,<BR> a putrid thing.<BR> It is neither sure nor substantial.|XI. OLD AGE 147
#This body wears out with age;<BR> it becomes a host to disease <BR> - vulnerable, fragile, <BR> a decrepit, disintegrating mass,<BR> which eventually ends in death.|XI. OLD AGE 148
#What pleasure does life hold<BR> once one has seen <BR> old bleached bones,<BR> discarded and scattered round?|XI. OLD AGE 149
#The physical body consists of bones <BR> covered with flesh and blood.<BR> Stored up inside it<BR> are decay and death, pride and malice.|XI. OLD AGE 150
#Passed down by the wise<BR> is the knowledge that,<BR> though what is externally impressive<BR> loses its splendour,<BR> and though our bodies will decay,<BR> the truth itself outlasts all degeneration.|XI. OLD AGE 151
#While ageing fools put on weight<BR> like oxen in their stalls,<BR> their minds remain small.|XI. OLD AGE 152
#For many lives I have wandered <BR> looking for, but not finding,<BR> the house-builder<BR> who caused my suffering.<BR> But now you are seen and<BR> you shall build no more.<BR> Your rafters are dislodged and <BR> the ridge-pole is broken.<BR> All craving is ended;<BR> my heart is as one with the unmade.|XI. OLD AGE 153-154
#Those who while still young<BR> neither choose a life of renunciation<BR> nor earn a good living,	<BR> end up like dejected old herons<BR> beside a pond without fish.|XI. OLD AGE 155
#Those who while still young<BR> neither choose a life of renunciation<BR> nor earn a good living,<BR> will end up bemoaning the past,<BR> falling like spent arrows <BR> that have missed their mark.|XI. OLD AGE 156
#If we hold ourselves dear, <BR> then we maintain careful self-regard<BR> both day and night.|XII. THE SELF 157
#It is wise <BR> to set ourselves right <BR> before instructing others.|XII. THE SELF 158
#One's own self is the hardest to discipline.<BR> You should act as you teach:<BR> tame yourself <BR> before trying to tame others. |XII. THE SELF 159
#Truly it is ourselves <BR> that we depend upon; <BR> how could we really <BR> depend upon another? <BR> When we reach the state <BR> of self reliance <BR> we find a rare refuge.|XII. THE SELF 160
#As a diamond can cut through<BR> the stone that once housed it,<BR> so your own evil can grind you down.|XII. THE SELF 161
#Committed evil doers <BR> behave toward themselves<BR> like their own worst enemies.<BR> They are like creepers <BR> that strangle the trees<BR> which support them.|XII. THE SELF 162
#It is easy to do that which is <BR> of no real benefit to oneself, <BR> but it is difficult indeed to do that <BR> which is truly beneficial and good.|XII. THE SELF 163
#Like the bamboo <BR> which destroys itself as it bears fruit,<BR> so fools harm themselves<BR> by holding to wrong views<BR> and deriding those worthy ones<BR> who live in harmony with the Way.|XII. THE SELF 164
#By ourselves we do evil <BR> and by ourselves we are made impure.<BR> By ourselves we avoid evil <BR> and by ourselves we are made pure. <BR> The great matter of purity <BR> is our own affair.<BR> No other can be responsible.|XII. THE SELF 165
#Knowing the Way for oneself,<BR> walk it thoroughly.<BR> Do not allow the needs of others, <BR> however demanding,<BR> to bring about distraction.|XII. THE SELF 166
#By renouncing unworthy ways <BR> and by not living carelessly, <BR> by not holding to false views <BR> we no longer perpetrate delusion.|XIII. THE WORLD 167
#Do not show false humility.<BR> Stand firmly in relation to your goal.<BR> Practice, well-observed,<BR> leads to contentment <BR> both now and in the future.|XIII. THE WORLD 168
#Live your life well in accord with the Way -<BR> avoid a life of distraction.<BR> A life well-lived leads to contentment,<BR> both now and in the future.|XIII. THE WORLD 169
#The King of Death cannot find <BR> those who look upon the world <BR> as insubstantial,<BR> as transient, a bubble -<BR> illusive, only a mirage.|XIII. THE WORLD 170
#Come, view this world.<BR> See it as an ornate, festive carriage. <BR> See how fools are entranced by their visions,<BR> yet, for the wise there is no attachment.|XIII. THE WORLD 171
#There are those who awaken from heedlessness. <BR> They bring light into the world<BR> like the moon <BR> emerging from clouds.|XIII. THE WORLD 172
#One who transforms old and heedless ways<BR> into fresh and wholesome acts<BR> brings light into the world<BR> like the moon freed from clouds.|XIII. THE WORLD 173
#If birds are trapped in a net <BR> only a few will ever escape. <BR> In this world of illusion<BR> only a few see their way to liberation.|XIII. THE WORLD 174
#White swans rise into the air.<BR> Adept yogis <BR> transport themselves through space. <BR> Wise beings <BR> transcend worldly delusion<BR> by outwitting the hordes of Mara.|XIII. THE WORLD 175
#For one who transgresses <BR> the law of truthfulness,<BR> one who has no regard<BR> for a future existence, <BR> there is no manner of evil <BR> that is impossible.|XIII. THE WORLD 176
#Those who fail to value generosity<BR> do not reach the celestial realms. <BR> But the wise rejoice in giving<BR> and forever abide in bliss.|XIII. THE WORLD 177
#Better than ruling the whole world, <BR> better than going to heaven, <BR> better than lordship over the universe,<BR> is an irreversible commitment to the Way.|XIII. THE WORLD 178
#The Buddha's perfection is complete;<BR> there is no more work to be done.<BR> No measure is there for his wisdom;<BR> no limits are there to be found.<BR> In what way could he be distracted <BR> from truth?|XIV. THE BUDDHA 179
#The Buddha's perfection is complete;<BR> in him there is no craving<BR> that could drag him down.<BR> No measure is there for his wisdom;<BR> no limits are there to be found.<BR> In what way could he be distracted <BR> from truth?|XIV. THE BUDDHA 180
#Celestial beings treasure <BR> the Awakened Ones <BR> who have fully seen the Way,<BR> who are devoted to meditation <BR> and delight in the peace <BR> of renunciation.|XIV. THE BUDDHA 181
#It is not easy to be born <BR> as a human being <BR> and to live this mortal life.<BR> It is not easy to discern <BR> profound wisdom <BR> and most rare <BR> for a Buddha to arise.|XIV. THE BUDDHA 182
#Cease to do evil,<BR> cultivate that which is good;<BR> purify the heart.<BR> This is the Way <BR> of the Awakened Ones.|XIV. THE BUDDHA 183
#A renunciate does not <BR> oppress anyone.<BR> Patient endurance <BR> is the ultimate asceticism.<BR> Profound liberation, <BR> say the Buddhas, <BR> is the supreme goal.|XIV. THE BUDDHA 184
#Not insulting, not harming,<BR> cultivating restraint <BR> with respect for the training,<BR> modesty in eating and contentment <BR> with one's dwelling place, <BR> devotion to mindful intent:<BR> this is the Teaching of the Buddha.|XIV. THE BUDDHA 185
#Not in great wealth <BR> is there contentment,<BR> nor in sensual pleasure, <BR> gross or refined. <BR> But in the extinction of craving <BR> is joy to be found<BR> by a disciple of the Buddha.|XIV. THE BUDDHA 186-187
#To many places beings withdraw <BR> to escape from fear:<BR> to mountains, forests, <BR> parklands and gardens; <BR> sacred places as well.<BR> But none of these places <BR> offer true refuge,<BR> none of them can free us from fear.|XIV. THE BUDDHA 188-189
#One who finds refuge in the Buddha<BR> in the Dhamma and in the Sangha <BR> sees with penetrating insight: <BR> suffering, its cause, its release <BR> and the Way leading to true freedom.|XIV. THE BUDDHA 190-191
#The Buddha, the Dhamma, the Sangha:<BR> these are true refuge;<BR> these are supreme;<BR> these lead to Liberation.|XIV. THE BUDDHA 192
#It is hard to find <BR> a being of great wisdom;<BR> rare are the places <BR> in which they are born.<BR> Those who surround them <BR> when they appear<BR> know good fortune indeed.|XIV. THE BUDDHA 193
#Blessed is the arising of a Buddha; <BR> blessed is the revealing of the Dhamma; <BR> blessed is the concord of the Sangha; <BR> delightful is harmonious communion.|XIV. THE BUDDHA 194
#Immeasurable is the benefit <BR> obtained from honouring those <BR> who are pure and beyond fear. <BR> Beings who have found freedom<BR> from sorrow and grieving <BR> are worthy of honour.|XIV. THE BUDDHA 195-196
#While in the midst <BR> of those who hate, <BR> to dwell free from hating <BR> is happiness indeed.|XV. HAPPINESS 197
#While in the midst <BR> of those who are troubled, <BR> to dwell free from troubling <BR> is happiness indeed.|XV. HAPPINESS 198
#While in the midst <BR> of those who are greedy, <BR> to dwell free from greed<BR> is happiness indeed.|XV. HAPPINESS 199
#We dwell happily, <BR> free from anxiety;<BR> like radiant beings <BR> in celestial realms <BR> we rejoice in delight.|XV. HAPPINESS 200
#Victory leads to hatred,<BR> for the defeated suffer.<BR> The peaceful live happily,<BR> beyond victory and defeat.|XV. HAPPINESS 201
#There is no fire like lust, <BR> no distress like hatred, <BR> no pain like the burden of attachment,<BR> no joy like the peace of liberation.|XV. HAPPINESS 202
#Hunger is the greatest affliction, <BR> conditionality the greatest <BR> source of despair. <BR> The wise, seeing this as it is,<BR> realise liberation, the greatest joy.|XV. HAPPINESS 203
#A healthy mind is the greatest gain.<BR> Contentment is the greatest wealth.<BR> A trustworthy friend is the best of kin. <BR> Unconditional freedom <BR> is the highest bliss.|XV. HAPPINESS 204
#Tasting the flavour of solitude<BR> and the nectar of peace,<BR> those who drink the joy<BR> that is the essence of reality <BR> abide free from fear of evil.|XV. HAPPINESS 205
#It is always a pleasure <BR> not to have to encounter fools. <BR> It is always good to see noble beings<BR> and a delight to live with them.|XV. HAPPINESS 206
#Tedious is the company of fools,<BR> always painful, like being<BR> surrounded by enemies;<BR> but to associate with the wise<BR> is like being at home.|XV. HAPPINESS 207
#You should follow the ways <BR> of those who are steadfast,<BR> discerning, pure and aware,<BR> just as the moon follows<BR> the path of the stars.|XV. HAPPINESS 208
#There are those who pursue <BR> that which should be avoided <BR> and avoid that which <BR> should be pursued.<BR> Caught up in the senses <BR> they lose their way <BR> and later envy<BR> those who know the truth.|XVI. AFFECTION 209
#To lose the company <BR> of those with whom <BR> one feels at home is painful,<BR> to be associated with those <BR> whom you dislike is even worse;<BR> so do not abandon yourselves<BR> either to the company of those<BR> with whom you feel at home<BR> or those whom you dislike.|XVI. AFFECTION 210
#Beware of the attachment<BR> that springs from fondness,<BR> for separation from those<BR> one holds dear is painful,<BR> while if you take sides <BR> neither for nor against fondness,<BR> there will be no bondage.|XVI. AFFECTION 211
#From endearment springs grief.<BR> From endearment springs fear of loss.<BR> Yet, if one is free from endearment, <BR> there is no grief<BR> so how could there be fear?|XVI. AFFECTION 212
#Becoming lost in affection <BR> brings sorrow; <BR> becoming lost in affection <BR> brings fear.<BR> Being free from affection <BR> means sorrow ceases, <BR> so how could there be any fear?|XVI. AFFECTION 213
#Becoming lost in enjoyment <BR> brings sorrow; <BR> becoming lost in enjoyment<BR> brings fear.<BR> Being free in your experience of enjoyment <BR> means sorrow ceases, <BR> so how could there be any fear?|XVI. AFFECTION 214
#Becoming lost in lust <BR> brings sorrow; <BR> becoming lost in lust <BR> brings fear.<BR> Not being lost in lust <BR> means sorrow ceases, <BR> so how could there be any fear?|XVI. AFFECTION 215
#Becoming lost in craving <BR> brings sorrow; <BR> becoming lost in craving<BR> brings fear.<BR> Being free from craving<BR> means sorrow ceases, <BR> so how could there be any fear?|XVI. AFFECTION 216
#Naturally loved are those <BR> who live with right action <BR> and have found the Way, <BR> and through insight <BR> have become established in the truth.|XVI. AFFECTION 217
#Those who long <BR> for the undefinable,<BR> with hearts filled with inspiration,<BR> whose minds are freed <BR> from sensual longing<BR> are called <BR> "those bound for freedom".|XVI. AFFECTION 218
#Just as family and friends<BR> joyfully welcome home<BR> loved ones returned from afar,<BR> so their own good deeds<BR> welcome those that have done them<BR> as they go from this life to the next.|XVI. AFFECTION 219-220
#Relinquish anger.<BR> Let go of conceit.<BR> Release yourself <BR> from all that binds you.<BR> The pure-hearted who cling <BR> neither to body or mind<BR> do not fall prey to suffering.|XVII. ANGER 221
#I say, those who contain anger<BR> as a charioteer controls <BR> a speeding chariot, <BR> are fully in charge of their lives;<BR> others are merely keeping <BR> their hands on the reins.|XVII. ANGER 222
#Transform anger with kindness <BR> and evil with good,<BR> meanness with generosity<BR> and deceit with integrity.|XVII. ANGER 223
#These three ways <BR> lead to the heavens:<BR> asserting the truth,<BR> not yielding to anger,<BR> and giving, even if you have <BR> only a little to share. |XVII. ANGER 224
#Awakened Ones do not cause harm. <BR> They are rightly restrained<BR> and they move to changelessness <BR> where they grieve no more.|XVII. ANGER 225
#All pollution is cleared <BR> from the minds of those <BR> who are always vigilant,<BR> training themselves day and night<BR> and whose lives are fully intent <BR> upon liberation.|XVII. ANGER 226
#Since ancient times it has been the case <BR> that those who speak too much <BR> are criticised, <BR> as are those who speak too little <BR> and those who don't speak at all. <BR> Everyone in this world is criticised.|XVII. ANGER 227
#There never was<BR> nor will there be<BR> nor is there now anybody <BR> who is only blamed <BR> or wholly praised.|XVII. ANGER 228
#Those who live impeccably,<BR> who are discerning, <BR> intelligent and virtuous - <BR> they are continually praised by the wise.|XVII. ANGER 229
#Who would cast blame on those <BR> who in their being are like gold?<BR> Even the gods appreciate their lustre.|XVII. ANGER 230
#Beware of clumsy movement <BR> and aware in your bodily conduct. <BR> Renounce all devious action<BR> and cultivate that which is wholesome.|XVII. ANGER 231
#Beware of contrived utterance <BR> and aware in all that you say.<BR> Renounce all cunning speech <BR> and cultivate that which is wholesome.|XVII. ANGER 232
#Beware of devious thinking<BR> and aware of all that you dwell upon.<BR> Renounce all unruly thought <BR> and cultivate that which is wholesome.|XVII. ANGER 233
#Ably self-restrained <BR> are the wise,<BR> in action, in thought <BR> and in speech.|XVII. ANGER 234
#Resembling a withered leaf, <BR> you have the messenger <BR> of death at your side. <BR> Although a long journey lies ahead, <BR> you have still made no provision.|XVIII. POLLUTION 235
#Hasten to cultivate wisdom. <BR> Make an island for yourself.<BR> Freed from stain and defilement, <BR> you will enter noble being.|XVIII. POLLUTION 236
#It is time for you to come<BR> into the presence of the Lord of Death. <BR> There is no time for rest on this journey,<BR> yet what provision have you made?|XVIII. POLLUTION 237
#Hasten to cultivate wisdom;<BR> make an island for yourself.<BR> Freed from stain and defilement<BR> you are released <BR> from birth and death.|XVIII. POLLUTION 238
#Gradually, gradually,<BR> a moment at a time,<BR> the wise remove their own impurities <BR> as a goldsmith removes the dross.|XVIII. POLLUTION 239
#As iron is destroyed by the rust it produces,  <BR> so those who perform evil are corroded<BR> by their own action.|XVIII. POLLUTION 240
#Lack of study leads  <BR> to forgetting the teachings; <BR> neglect spoils the home; <BR> laziness leads to loss of beauty; <BR> heedlessness ruins attention.|XVIII. POLLUTION 241
#Sexual misconduct <BR> diminishes those who perform it,<BR> stinginess diminishes <BR> those who could give.<BR> Acts that diminish their doer <BR> are stains indeed.|XVIII. POLLUTION 242
#But the worst stain of all <BR> is ignorance. <BR> Be purified of this <BR> and you are free.|XVIII. POLLUTION 243
#Life is apparently easy <BR> for one who lacks shame, <BR> who is as impudent as a crow,<BR> who is arrogant, aggressive, <BR> invasive and corrupt.|XVIII. POLLUTION 244
#Life is not easy for those <BR> who have a sense of shame, <BR> who are modest, <BR> pure-minded and detached,<BR> morally upright and reflective.|XVIII. POLLUTION 245
#Whoever destroys life, <BR> disregards truth,<BR> is sexually irresponsible,<BR> takes what is not rightfully theirs, <BR> and heedlessly indulges in drugs,<BR> destroys the very roots <BR> of their own life.|XVIII. POLLUTION 246-247
#Whoever is intent on goodness<BR> should know this:<BR> a lack of self-restraint is disastrous.<BR> Do not allow  greed and misconduct <BR> to prolong your misery.|XVIII. POLLUTION 248
#People are inspired to be generous <BR> according to their faith and trust. <BR> If we become discontented<BR> with what we have been given<BR> our meditation will be filled<BR> with endless mental affliction;<BR> but if we are free from this discontent, <BR> our meditation is full of  peace.|XVIII. POLLUTION 249-250
#There is no fire like lust,<BR> no obstruction like hatred,<BR> no trap like delusion,<BR> and no vortex like craving.|XVIII. POLLUTION 251
#It is easy to see the faults of others, <BR> but it takes courage to look at one's own.<BR> As with chaff,<BR> one might winnow others' shortcomings<BR> while hiding one's own,<BR> as a stealthy hunter<BR> might conceal himself from his prey. |XVIII. POLLUTION 252
#Those who always look for <BR> the faults of others - <BR> their corruptions increase<BR> and they are far from freedom.|XVIII. POLLUTION 253
