#Silence does not denote profundity<BR> if you are ignorant and untrained.<BR> Like one holding scales,<BR> a sage weighs things up, <BR> wholesome and unwholesome, <BR> and comes to know <BR> both the inner and outer worlds. <BR> Therefore the sage is called wise.|XIX. THE JUST 268-269
#Those who still cause harm <BR> to living beings <BR> cannot be considered as attained.<BR> Those who are attained<BR> maintain a harmless demeanour<BR> toward all beings.|XIX. THE JUST 270
#Do not rest contented<BR> because you keep all the rules and regulations,<BR> nor because you achieve great learning.<BR> Do not feel satisfied because you<BR> attain meditative absorption,<BR> nor because you can dwell in <BR> the bliss of solitude.<BR> Only when you arrive <BR> at the complete eradication<BR> of all ignorance and conceit<BR> should you be content.|XIX. THE JUST 270-271
#The eight-fold path <BR> is the most honourable way,<BR> the four noble truths <BR> the most honourable utterance,<BR> freedom from craving <BR> the most honourable state,<BR> and the all-seeing Buddha <BR> the most honourable being.|XX. THE PATH 273
#This is the only Way;<BR> there is no other <BR> that leads to clear seeing.<BR> Follow this Way<BR> and Mara becomes disoriented.|XX. THE PATH 274
#If you walk the path<BR> you will arrive at the end of suffering.<BR> Having beheld this myself,<BR> I proclaim the Way <BR> which removes all thorns.|XX. THE PATH 275
#The Awakened Ones <BR> can but point the way; <BR> we must make the effort ourselves.<BR> Those who reflect wisely<BR> and enter the path are freed <BR> from the fetters of Mara.|XX. THE PATH 276
#"All conditioned things are impermanent"; <BR> when we see this with insight <BR> we will tire of this life of suffering. <BR> This is the Way to purification.|XX. THE PATH 277
