#The clear seeing which knows<BR> that which is flawed as flawed<BR> and that which is pure as pure<BR> can lead beings to transcend misery.|XXII. HELL 319
#Like an elephant in battle<BR> withstands arrows,<BR> I choose to endure <BR> verbal attacks from others.|XXIII. THE ELEPHANT 320
#Well-trained horses <BR> can be trusted in crowds,<BR> and are to be mounted by kings.<BR> Individuals who have trained <BR> themselves to withstand abuse<BR> will be valuable everywhere.|XXIII. THE ELEPHANT 321
#Impressive are horses or elephants<BR> which have been well-trained;<BR> but more impressive<BR> are individuals<BR> who have tamed themselves.|XXIII. THE ELEPHANT 322
#It is not on a well-trained animal<BR> that you can ride<BR> to the land of liberation;<BR> it is only on the vehicle <BR> of a well-trained self <BR> that you will arrive there.|XXIII. THE ELEPHANT 323
#A wild elephant <BR> when captured and bound and in rut<BR> is restless, uncontrollable,<BR> not eating its food.<BR> It longs for its native forest home.|XXIII. THE ELEPHANT 324
#It is a fool that overeats<BR> and indulges in laziness,<BR> then, feeling drowsy,<BR> wallows in sleep like an oversized pig;	 <BR> this forebodes perpetual suffering.|XXIII. THE ELEPHANT 325
#My mind which was once <BR> wild and unruly,<BR> wandering as it wished,<BR> I hold now in check, <BR> as the mahout with his hook<BR> controls an elephant in rut.|XXIII. THE ELEPHANT 326
#As an elephant <BR> resolutely drags itself from a swamp<BR> uplift yourself with the inspiration <BR> of cultivated attention.|XXIII. THE ELEPHANT 327
#If you find a good companion,<BR> of integrity and wisdom,<BR> you will overcome all dangers<BR> in joyous and caring company.|XXIII. THE ELEPHANT 328
#But if you cannot find <BR> a good companion<BR> of integrity and wisdom,<BR> then, like a king departing <BR> a conquered land,<BR> or an elephant wandering <BR> alone in the forest,<BR> walk alone.|XXIII. THE ELEPHANT 329
#A harmless solitary life <BR> lived at ease <BR> like that of the lone elephant in the forest,<BR> is better than <BR> the unnecessary company of fools.|XXIII. THE ELEPHANT 330
#Pleasure arises from <BR> the timely company of friends.<BR> Pleasure arises from <BR> having few needs.<BR> Pleasure arises from <BR> accumulated virtue at life's end.<BR> Pleasure arises from <BR> seeing beyond suffering.|XXIII. THE ELEPHANT 331
#Pleasure arises from <BR> rightly serving one's parents.<BR> Pleasure arises from <BR> supporting renunciates.<BR> Pleasure arises from <BR> honouring awakened beings.|XXIII. THE ELEPHANT 332
#Pleasure arises from <BR> sustaining virtue into old age.<BR> Pleasure arises from <BR> sustaining sound faith.<BR> Pleasure arises with insight. <BR> Pleasure arises from <BR> renouncing evil.|XXIII. THE ELEPHANT 333
#Uncontained craving <BR> grows like a creeper in the forest.<BR> Being lost in it<BR> one leaps around <BR> like a tree-dwelling ape looking for fruit.|XXIV. CRAVING 334
#Fostering habits <BR> such as craving and clinging<BR> is like fertilising noxious weeds.|XXIV. CRAVING 335
#As water falls from a lotus leaf<BR> so sorrow drops from those <BR> who are free of toxic craving.|XXIV. CRAVING 336
#Torrential rains can destroy crops.<BR> Mara can destroy you.<BR> Thus I implore you ?<BR> dig up the roots of all craving.<BR> I give you my blessing<BR> for this work.|XXIV. CRAVING 337
#If the roots are not removed<BR> a tree grows again and again;<BR> suffering returns to us<BR> so long as craving remains.|XXIV. CRAVING 338
#When the streams <BR> of sensual pleasure run strong<BR> they can generate <BR> a torrent of longing.|XXIV. CRAVING 339
#The streams of craving flow everywhere. <BR> The wild creeper of craving<BR> spreads and entangles.<BR> Discerning this creeper with insight,<BR> dig it out.|XXIV. CRAVING 340
#Beings naturally experience pleasure;<BR> but when pleasure is contaminated with craving,<BR> not releasing it creates frustration <BR> and tedious suffering follows.|XXIV. CRAVING 341
#Trapped in habits of craving <BR> people panic <BR> like rabbits caught in the snare.<BR> Their reactions reinforce the pain<BR> of their entrapment. |XXIV. CRAVING 342
#Trapped in habits of craving <BR> people panic <BR> like rabbits caught in the snare.<BR> If you wish to be free from entrapment,<BR> craving itself must be removed. |XXIV. CRAVING 343
#There are those who have begun <BR> on the path to freedom<BR> yet return, out of desire, to bondage.|XXIV. CRAVING 344
#Wisdom sees <BR> that being held behind bars <BR> or bound by chains<BR> is less limiting <BR> than infatuation with possessions <BR> and obsession with relationships.<BR> These bonds, though not so obvious,<BR> are strong and hold us down.<BR> To renounce attachment <BR> to the world of the senses<BR> is to be free from the prison of craving.|XXIV. CRAVING 345-346
#Like a spider caught in its own web,<BR> a being enwrapped in sensual craving<BR> must be released from its own longings<BR> before it can walk free.|XXIV. CRAVING 347
#Let go of the past.<BR> Let go of the future.<BR> Let go of the present.<BR> With a heart that is free<BR> cross over to that shore<BR> which is beyond suffering.|XXIV. CRAVING 348
#The bonds <BR> of deluded habits and craving <BR> are strengthened<BR> by one who lets the mind heedlessly dwell<BR> on objects of desire.|XXIV. CRAVING 349
#But one who delights<BR> in calming sensual thoughts,<BR> who is alert <BR> and cultivates awareness <BR> of the loathsome <BR> aspects of the body, <BR> breaks through craving<BR> and unbinds deluded habits.|XXIV. CRAVING 350
#No more need is there to re-form<BR> for those who have reached the goal;<BR> they are free from fear and longing.<BR> The thorns of existence have been removed.|XXIV. CRAVING 351
#A master is one who has let go<BR> of all craving and clinging to the world;<BR> who has seen <BR> the truth beyond forms,<BR> yet is possessed of <BR> a profound knowledge of words.<BR> Such a great being can be said <BR> to have finished the task.|XXIV. CRAVING 352
#I do not declare <BR> another as my teacher <BR> since by myself have I arrived <BR> at the wisdom that overcomes all,<BR> realises all, renounces all.<BR> Wholly liberated am I<BR> from all craving.|XXIV. CRAVING 353
#The gift of truth excels all gifts.<BR> The flavour of reality <BR> surpasses all flavours.<BR> The delight of truth <BR> transcends all delights.<BR> Freedom from craving<BR> is the end of all suffering.|XXIV. CRAVING 354
#Riches mostly ruin the foolish	<BR> but not those who seek the beyond.<BR> Just as they dismiss <BR> the well-being of others and cause harm,<BR> fools also ruin themselves.|XXIV. CRAVING 355
#Weeds cause damage in fields.<BR> Lust causes damage to all beings.<BR> Support those who are free from lust;<BR> the gift will yield great benefit.|XXIV. CRAVING 356
#Weeds cause damage in fields. <BR> Hatred causes damage to all beings.<BR> Support those who are free from hatred;<BR> the gift will yield great benefit.|XXIV. CRAVING 357
#Weeds cause damage in fields.<BR> Confusion causes damage to all beings.<BR> Support those who are free from confusion;<BR> the gift will yield great benefit.|XXIV. CRAVING 358
#Weeds cause damage in fields.<BR> Envy causes damage to all beings.<BR> Encourage those who are free from envy <BR> and there will be great benefit.|XXIV. CRAVING 359
#It is good to restrain the eye.<BR> It is good to restrain the ear. <BR> It is good to restrain the nose. <BR> It is good to restrain the tongue.|XXV. THE RENUNCIATE 360
#It is good to be restrained in body. <BR> It is good to be restrained in speech. <BR> It is good to be restrained in the mind. <BR> It is good to be restrained <BR> in everything. <BR> The renunciate who is restrained <BR> in every way will realise freedom <BR> from suffering.|XXV. THE RENUNCIATE 361
#One who is rightly disciplined <BR> in all actions,<BR> who is composed, <BR> contented and delights in <BR> solitary contemplation -<BR> such is a renunciate.|XXV. THE RENUNCIATE 362
#It is pleasing to hear<BR> the words of a renunciate<BR> who is wise, not inflated, <BR> whose mind is composed<BR> and whose speech is contained<BR> and clear in meaning.|XXV. THE RENUNCIATE 363
#One who abides in Dhamma,<BR> who delights in Dhamma,<BR> who contemplates Dhamma,<BR> who memorises Dhamma<BR> does not lose the Way.|XXV. THE RENUNCIATE 364
#Bemoaning your own lot <BR> or envying the gains of others <BR> obstructs peace of mind.|XXV. THE RENUNCIATE 365
#But, being contented<BR> even with modest gains<BR> pure in livelihood and energetic,<BR> you will be held in high esteem. |XXV. THE RENUNCIATE 366
#True renunciates<BR> regard the entire body-mind <BR> without any thought of 'I' or 'mine'<BR> and are devoid of longing <BR> for what they do not have.|XXV. THE RENUNCIATE 367
#A renunciate who <BR> abides in loving-kindness<BR> with a heart full of devotion <BR> for the Buddha's teaching<BR> will find peace, stillness and bliss.|XXV. THE RENUNCIATE 368
#Bale out the water from your boat;<BR> cut loose from the defiling passions <BR> of lust and hatred;<BR> unencumbered, sail on<BR> towards liberation.|XXV. THE RENUNCIATE 369
#One who has<BR> cut off coarse attachments,<BR> cut off subtle attachments,<BR> who cultivates the spiritual faculties,<BR> is the one who finds freedom <BR> from delusion.|XXV. THE RENUNCIATE 370
#Be careful!<BR> Do not neglect meditation,<BR> nor allow the mind <BR> to dwell on sensuality<BR> lest you might heedlessly swallow<BR> a red-hot ball of iron<BR> and find yourself crying out, "why am I suffering?"|XXV. THE RENUNCIATE 371
#Concentration does not arise<BR> without understanding,<BR> nor understanding <BR> without concentration.<BR> One who knows both <BR> approaches liberation.|XXV. THE RENUNCIATE 372
#A happiness transcending ordinary bliss <BR> is experienced by those renunciates <BR> who have entered into seclusion<BR> with tranquil heart<BR> and clear understanding of the Way.|XXV. THE RENUNCIATE 373
#When those who are wise <BR> dwell in contemplation<BR> on the transient nature<BR> of the body-mind,<BR> and of all conditioned existence,<BR> they experience joy and delight<BR> seeing through <BR> to the inherently secure. |XXV. THE RENUNCIATE 374
#This then is the beginning <BR> for a renunciate <BR> who takes up the training:<BR> wisely control your faculties,<BR> commit yourself to the instruction,<BR> seek contentment;<BR> cultivate the company of those <BR> who support your aspiration<BR> for energetic practice of the teachings.<BR> The beauty of pure conduct <BR> conditions whole-hearted well-being<BR> giving rise to complete <BR> freedom from remorse.|XXV. THE RENUNCIATE 375-376
#As old flowers fall <BR> from a jasmine plant<BR> let lust and hatred<BR> fall away.|XXV. THE RENUNCIATE 377
#I call them the peaceful ones,	<BR> who are calm in body,<BR> in speech and in mind,<BR> and who are thoroughly purged <BR> of all worldly obsessions.|XXV. THE RENUNCIATE 378
#Scrutinise yourself.<BR> Examine yourself.<BR> With right attention <BR> to self assessment<BR> you will live at ease.|XXV. THE RENUNCIATE 379
#We are our own protection;<BR> we are indeed our own secure abiding;<BR> how could it be otherwise?<BR> So with due care<BR> we attend to ourselves.|XXV. THE RENUNCIATE 380
#A monk, a nun, who cultivates<BR> a joyous disposition<BR> and is filled with <BR> confidence in the Way<BR> will find peace, stillness and bliss.|XXV. THE RENUNCIATE 381
#Yet still a youth, a renunciate <BR> fully devoted to the Way<BR> lights up the world<BR> like the moon emerging from clouds.|XXV. THE RENUNCIATE 382
#Diligently cut off <BR> the stream of craving <BR> and abandon sensual longings;<BR> knowing the limitation<BR> of all that is formed,<BR> realise the uncreated.|XXVI. GREAT BEING 383
#All chains of bondage fall away<BR> from those who see clearly<BR> and know well the states <BR> of concentration and insight.|XXVI. GREAT BEING 384
#I say a being is great<BR> who stands not on this shore,<BR> nor the other shore,<BR> nor on any shore at all.<BR> Such a being is free from all ties.|XXVI. GREAT BEING 385
#I say a being is great<BR> who dwells secluded and at ease, <BR> knowing the heart <BR> free from all pollution,<BR> having completed the task<BR> purified of all compulsive tendencies,	<BR> and awake.|XXVI. GREAT BEING 386
#The sun shines by day,<BR> the moon shines by night.<BR> But, both all day and all night<BR> the Buddha shines <BR> in glorious splendour.|XXVI. GREAT BEING 387
#Having transformed evil<BR> one is called a great being.<BR> Living peacefully<BR> one is called a contemplative.<BR> Having given up impurity<BR> one is called a renunciate.|XXVI. GREAT BEING 388
#Non-retaliation <BR> is the characteristic of great beings.<BR> They do not give rise to anger.<BR> Should they be attacked, <BR> it is not in their nature to strike back.|XXVI. GREAT BEING 389
#Suffering subsides to the degree <BR> that you are free from the intention<BR> to cause harm.<BR> There is no real greatness<BR> if there is no restraint from anger.|XXVI. GREAT BEING 390
#One who refrains from causing harm<BR> by way of body, speech or mind,<BR> can be called a worthy being.|XXVI. GREAT BEING 391
#Devotion and respect<BR> should be offered to those <BR> who have shown us the Way.|XXVI. GREAT BEING 392
#One should not be considered <BR> worthy of respect<BR> because of birth or background<BR> or any outer sign;<BR> it is purity <BR> and the realisation of truth <BR> that determine one's worth.|XXVI. GREAT BEING 393
#Your outer adornments <BR> and pseudo-spiritual preoccupations<BR> are irrelevant<BR> if inwardly you remain in disarray.|XXVI. GREAT BEING 394
#To be unconcerned <BR> about outer appearance,<BR> but committed to <BR> intense relentless practice<BR> makes for greatness.|XXVI. GREAT BEING 395
#No one is noble <BR> merely because of what they inherit.<BR> Nobility comes from cleansing oneself<BR> of all pollutions <BR> and attachments.|XXVI. GREAT BEING 396
#Whoever has broken lose from all bondage<BR> and found fearlessness,<BR> who is beyond attachments <BR> and defilements,<BR> I recognise as a great being.|XXVI. GREAT BEING 397
#Whoever severs the ties of hatred,<BR> unbinds the ropes of craving,<BR> undoes the locks of wrong view,<BR> opens the doors of ignorance,<BR> and sees truth,<BR> I recognise as a great being.|XXVI. GREAT BEING 398
#Strength of patience <BR> is the might of noble beings;<BR> they can be shackled,<BR> endure verbal abuse and beatings,<BR> without resorting to anger.|XXVI. GREAT BEING 399
#Those who are free from anger,<BR> simply disciplined, virtuous, <BR> well trained, <BR> and have gone beyond rebirth,<BR> these I call great beings.|XXVI. GREAT BEING 400
#As water slides from a lotus leaf,<BR> so sensual pleasures<BR> do not cling <BR> to a great being.|XXVI. GREAT BEING 401
#Those who know the freedom <BR> of having laid aside <BR> the burden of attachment <BR> to the body-mind<BR> I call great beings.|XXVI. GREAT BEING 402
#Those possessed of deep wisdom,<BR> who see what accords with the Way <BR> and what does not,<BR> those who have attained <BR> to the peak of possibility,<BR> I call great beings.|XXVI. GREAT BEING 403
#Those who are free from attachment <BR> to the company of either householders<BR> or fellow renunciates,<BR> and so wander free from desires <BR> or concern for security of any kind,<BR> are great beings.|XXVI. GREAT BEING 404
#Those who have renounced <BR> the use of force <BR> in relationship to other beings	<BR> whether weak or strong,<BR> who neither kill <BR> nor cause to be killed,<BR> can be called great beings. |XXVI. GREAT BEING 405
#Those who remain<BR> friendly amid the hostile,<BR> at peace among the aggressive,<BR> and who do not attach themselves<BR> to that upon which others depend <BR> are great beings.|XXVI. GREAT BEING 406
#For a great being,<BR> lust and ill-will, <BR> arrogance and conceit <BR> drop away<BR> even as a tiny seed would drop<BR> from the tip of a needle.|XXVI. GREAT BEING 407
#Those who speak truth<BR> and give gentle encouragement, <BR> contending with no-one,<BR> these do I call great beings.|XXVI. GREAT BEING 408
#The actions of a great being are pure.<BR> Great beings never <BR> knowingly take for themselves	<BR> that which belongs to another.	|XXVI. GREAT BEING 409
#The heart of a great being is free. <BR> Great beings no longer pine<BR> for things of this world <BR> or any other world.|XXVI. GREAT BEING 410
#The heart of a great being is free. <BR> With accurate understanding<BR> which is beyond doubt,<BR> great beings have set their feet firmly <BR> in the land of liberation.|XXVI. GREAT BEING 411
#Whoever has transcended<BR> all ties of good and bad<BR> is purified,<BR> and free from sorrow,<BR> should be called a great being.|XXVI. GREAT BEING 412
#Those beings who <BR> are released from all longing<BR> and, like the moon in a cloudless sky,<BR> are pure, clear and serene,<BR> I call great. |XXVI. GREAT BEING 413
#There are beings <BR> who travel the difficult path<BR> across the dangerous swamp <BR> of defiling passions,<BR> traverse the ocean of delusion<BR> through the darkness of ignorance,<BR> and go beyond.<BR> They are sustained <BR> by wise contemplation,<BR> secure in freedom from doubt,<BR> liberated;<BR> such beings are great indeed.|XXVI. GREAT BEING 414
#It is a great being <BR> who, having restrained desires <BR> for sensual pleasure, <BR> lives the homeless life<BR> and realises freedom<BR> from both sensual desire<BR> and perpetual becoming.|XXVI. GREAT BEING 415
#It is a great being <BR> who, having restrained all craving,<BR> lives the homeless life<BR> and realises freedom<BR> from both craving<BR> and perpetual becoming.|XXVI. GREAT BEING 416
#It is a great being <BR> who can see through all obvious delights<BR> as well as subtle pleasures<BR> to be free from attachment.|XXVI. GREAT BEING 417
#Those who cease <BR> setting up like against dislike,<BR> who are cooled,<BR> who are not swayed <BR> by worldly conditions -<BR> these I call great beings.|XXVI. GREAT BEING 418
#I say anyone who understands fully<BR> the passing away and arising of beings,<BR> who remains aware, <BR> non-attached, awake,<BR> who is conscious of <BR> right action at all times,<BR> is a great being.|XXVI. GREAT BEING 419
#The condition after death<BR> of great beings is indiscernible;<BR> no trace of passion remains.<BR> They are pure.|XXVI. GREAT BEING 420
#Anyone who lives freed <BR> from habits of clinging, <BR> to past, present or future,<BR> possessing nothing,<BR> is a great being.|XXVI. GREAT BEING 421
#A great being is fearless like a bull, <BR> noble, strong, wise, diligent,<BR> sees through delusions,<BR> is clear, attentive and awake.|XXVI. GREAT BEING 422
#To understand all dimensions <BR> of past existence,<BR> to see accurately into all realms,<BR> to reach the end of rebirths,<BR> to know with insight <BR> that which must be known,<BR> to free the heart from ignorance<BR> this is truly being made great.|XXVI. GREAT BEING 423
